# Modern Java Features

## Records (Java 16+)
- Use for immutable data carriers: DTOs, value objects, configuration holders
- Prefer compact constructors for validation
- Do not add mutable fields, setters, or excessive logic
- Records may implement interfaces but cannot extend classes

## Sealed Classes (Java 17+)
- Model closed type hierarchies: `sealed class Shape permits Circle, Rectangle`
- All permitted subclasses must be `final`, `sealed`, or `non-sealed`
- Enables exhaustive `switch` -- compiler verifies all subtypes handled
- Keep subclasses in the same package or same file for small hierarchies

## Pattern Matching
- `instanceof` pattern (Java 16+): `if (obj instanceof String s)` -- eliminates explicit cast
- Switch pattern (Java 21): use for type-safe dispatch over sealed hierarchies
- Record patterns (Java 21): `case Point(int x, int y)` for destructuring
- Guard clauses in switch: `case String s when s.length() > 10`

## Modern Switch
- Arrow syntax (`->`) for all new switch statements and expressions
- Switch expressions return values -- assign or return directly
- Exhaustive switch over sealed types and enums (no default needed when all cases covered)

## Text Blocks
- Use `"""` for multi-line strings (SQL, JSON, HTML templates)
- Mind trailing whitespace with `\s` escape or `.stripIndent()`

## Local Variable Type Inference
- `var` only when the type is obvious from the right-hand side
- Do not use `var` for diamond inference ambiguity or method return types that are unclear

## Sequenced Collections (Java 21)
- `SequencedCollection`: `getFirst()`, `getLast()`, `reversed()`
- `SequencedMap`: `firstEntry()`, `lastEntry()`, `sequencedKeySet()`
- Prefer over index-based access (`list.get(0)`, `list.get(list.size()-1)`)

## Data-Oriented Programming
- Combine sealed interfaces + records + pattern matching for algebraic data types
- Model domain events and commands as sealed hierarchies of records
- Exhaustive switch for processing -- compiler ensures completeness

## Anti-Patterns
- Do not use records as mutable containers
- Do not reflexively add `default` to switches over sealed types (defeats exhaustiveness checking)
- Do not use `var` everywhere -- readability is the priority

